{"title_page": "Isolation (health care)", "text_new": "{{short description|Measure taken to prevent contagious diseases from being spread}}\n{{distinguish|biocontainment|quarantine}}\n{{other uses|Isolation (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:Tb ward.jpg|thumb|365px|This illustration of a TB ward from [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration|OSHA]] demonstrates several aspects of hospital [[infection control]] and '''isolation''': engineering controls (dedicated air ductwork), [[Personal protective equipment|PPE]] ([[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 respirators]]), warning signs and labels (controlled entry), dedicated disposal container, and enhanced housekeeping practices.]]\n\nIn [[health care facilities]], '''isolation''' represents one of several measures that can be taken to implement [[infection control]]: the prevention of [[contagious disease]]s from being spread from a [[patient]] to other patients, health care workers, and visitors, or from outsiders to a particular patient (reverse isolation). Various forms of isolation exist, in some of which contact procedures are modified, and others in which the patient is kept away from all others. In a system devised, and periodically revised, by the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC), various levels of patient isolation comprise application of one or more formally described \"precaution\".\n\nIsolation is most commonly used when a patient is known to have a contagious ([[Transmission (medicine)|transmissible]] from person-to-person) [[viral illness|viral]] or [[Bacteria|bacterial illness]].<ref name=\"LawrenceMay2003a\">{{cite book|author1=Lawrence J|author2=May D|title=Infection control in the community|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKK2QI8AhTgC&pg=PA136|year=2003|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-443-06406-7|page=136}}</ref> Special equipment is used in the management of patients in the various forms of isolation. These most commonly include items of [[personal protective equipment]] ([[cleanroom suit|gowns]], [[surgical mask|masks]], and [[medical glove|gloves]]) and engineering controls (positive pressure rooms, [[Negative room pressure|negative pressure rooms]], laminar air flow equipment, and various mechanical and structural barriers).<ref name=\"Uys249\">{{cite book|author=Uys LR|title=Fundamental nursing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LILWN0VQuGQC&pg=RA1-PA249|year=1999|publisher=Pearson South Africa|isbn=978-0-636-04208-7|page=249}}</ref> Dedicated [[isolation ward]]s may be pre-built into hospitals, or isolation units may be temporarily designated in facilities in the midst of an [[epidemic]] emergency.\n\n== Importance ==\n[[Infection|Contagious diseases]] can spread to others through various forms. Four types of infectious disease [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] can occur: (1) contact transmission, which can be through direct physical contact, indirect contact through fomites, or droplet contact in which airborne infections spread short distances, (2) vehicular transmission, which involves contaminated objects, (3) [[airborne transmission]], which involves spread of infectious particles through air, and (4) vector transmission, which is spread through insects or animals.<ref>{{cite book |vauthors=Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW, McCue JD |title=The Contagious Patient |date=1990 |url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK337/ |work=Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations |veditors=Walker HK, Dallas W, Willis J |edition=3rd |publisher=Butterworths |isbn=978-0-409-90077-4 |pmid=21250179}}</ref> Depending on the [[contagious disease]], transmission can occur within a person's home, school, worksite, health care facility, and other shared spaces within the community. Even if a person takes all necessary precautions to protect oneself from disease, such as being up-to-date with [[Vaccine|vaccines]] and practicing good [[hygiene]], he or she can still get sick. Some people may not be able to protect themselves from diseases and may develop serious complications if they contract the disease. Therefore, disease isolation is an important infection prevention and control practice used to protect others from disease.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Swanson J, Jeanes A |title=Infection control in the community: a pragmatic approach |journal=British Journal of Community Nursing |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=282\u20138 |date=June 2011 |pmid=21642912 |doi=10.12968/bjcn.2011.16.6.282}}</ref> Disease isolation can prevent healthcare-acquired infections of [[Hospital-acquired infection|hospital-acquired infections]] (HCAIs), reduce threats of [[Antimicrobial resistance|antibiotic resistance infections]], and respond to new and emerging infectious disease threats globally.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gammon J, Hunt J |title=A review of isolation practices and procedures in healthcare settings |journal=British Journal of Nursing |volume=27 |issue=3 |pages=137\u2013140 |date=February 2018 |pmid=29412028 |doi=10.12968/bjon.2018.27.3.137}}</ref>\n\n== Types of precautions ==\nThe U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) created various levels of disease isolation (also described \"precaution\"). These precautions are also reviewed and revised by the CDC.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/infectioncontrol/basics/standard-precautions.html |title=Standard Precautions for All Patient Care {{!}} Basics {{!}} Infection Control {{!}} CDC|date=2019-03-25|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Universal/standard ===\n{{main|Universal precautions}}\n''Universal precautions''  refer to the practice, in [[medicine]], of avoiding contact with patients' bodily fluids, by means of the wearing of nonporous articles such as [[medical gloves]], [[goggles]], and [[face shield]]s. The practice was widely introduced in 1985\u201388.<ref name=\"pmid2836717\">{{cite journal |author=Centers for Disease Control (CDC) |title=Update: universal precautions for prevention of transmission of human immunodeficiency virus, hepatitis B virus, and other bloodborne pathogens in health-care settings |journal=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |volume=37 |issue=24 |pages=377\u201382, 387\u20138 |date=June 1988 |pmid=2836717 |doi= |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00000039.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid2997587\">{{cite journal |author=Centers for Disease Control (CDC) |title=Recommendations for preventing transmission of infection with human T-lymphotropic virus type III/lymphadenopathy-associated virus in the workplace |journal=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |volume=34 |issue=45 |pages=681\u20136, 691\u20135 |date=November 1985 |pmid=2997587 |doi= |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00033093.htm}}</ref> In 1987, the practice of universal precautions was adjusted by a set of rules known as [[body substance isolation]]. In 1996, both practices were replaced by the latest approach known as standard precautions. Use of [[personal protective equipment]] is now recommended in all health settings.\n\n=== Transmission-based ===\n{{main|Transmission-based precautions}}\n\n''Transmission-based precautions'' are additional [[infection control]] precautions \u2013 over and above universal/standard precautions \u2013 and the latest routine infection prevention and control practices applied for patients who are known or suspected to be infected or colonized with infectious agents, including certain [[Epidemiology|epidemiologically]] important [[pathogen]]s. The latter require additional control measures to effectively prevent transmission.<ref name=\"autogenerated2007\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Siegel JD, Rhinehart E, Jackson M, Chiarello L |title=2007 Guideline for Isolation Precautions: Preventing Transmission of Infectious Agents in Health Care Settings |journal=American Journal of Infection Control |volume=35 |issue=10 Suppl 2 |pages=S65\u2013164 |date=December 2007 |pmid=18068815 |doi=10.1016/j.ajic.2007.10.007}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Infection prevention and control of epidemic- and pandemic-prone acute respiratory diseases in health care, WHO Interim Guidelines |date=2007 |page=53 ||</ref>There are three types of transmission-based precaution:\n*'''''Contact precautions''''' are intended to prevent transmission of infectious agents, including epidemiologically important [[microorganism]]s, which are spread by direct or indirect contact with the patient or the patient's environment.\n*'''''Droplet precautions''''' are intended to prevent transmission of pathogens spread through close respiratory or mucous membrane contact with respiratory secretions.\n*'''''Airborne precautions''''' prevent transmission of infectious agents that remain infectious over long distances when suspended in the air (e.g., rubeola virus [measles], varicella virus [chickenpox], M. tuberculosis, and possibly SARS-CoV).\n\n=== Isolation ===\nAccording to the CDC, isolation is used to protect the general public from possible exposure of a contagious disease. ''Isolation'' is the act of separating a sick individual with a contagious disease from healthy individuals without that contagious disease.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/index.html |title=Quarantine and Isolation {{!}} Quarantine {{!}} |date=2018-10-03| work = Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\nSpecial equipment is used in the management of patients in the various forms of isolation. These most commonly include items of [[personal protective equipment]] ([[Cleanroom suit|gowns]], [[Surgical mask|masks]], and [[Medical glove|gloves]]) and engineering controls (positive pressure rooms, negative pressure rooms, laminar air flow equipment, and various mechanical and structural barriers). Dedicated [[Isolation ward|isolation wards]] may be pre-built into hospitals, or isolation units may be temporarily designated in facilities in the midst of an epidemic emergency.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.loot.co.za/product/leana-uys-fundamental-nursing/mkkm-180-g460 |title=Fundamental Nursing - Textbook (Paperback) |publisher=Leana Uys |isbn=978-0-636-04208-7 |access-date=2019-05-01 |year=2003}}</ref>\n\nIsolation should not be mistaken as the same as [[quarantine]] or biocontainment. [[Quarantine]] is the compulsory separation and confinement, with restriction of movement, of healthy individuals or groups who have potentially been exposed to an agent to prevent further infections should infection occur. [[Biocontainment]] refers to laboratory biosafety in microbiology laboratories in which the physical containment (BSL-3, BSL-4) of highly pathogenic organisms is accomplished through built-in engineering controls.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/index.html |title=Quarantine and Isolation {{!}} Quarantine {{!}} | work = Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |date=2018-10-03 |access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\nMany forms of isolation exist.\n\n====Strict isolation====\n'''Strict isolation''' is used for diseases spread through the air and in some cases by contact.<ref name=\"Uys249\"/> Patients must be placed in isolation to prevent the spread of infectious diseases.<ref name=\"WHITE2004\">{{cite book |author=White L |title=Foundations of nursing |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xSFunA58p8gC&pg=PA757 |date=2004 |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-1-4018-2692-5 |page=757}}</ref> Those who are kept in strict isolation are often kept in a special room at the facility designed for that purpose. Such rooms are equipped with a special [[toilet|lavatory]] and caregiving equipment, and a sink and waste disposal are provided for workers upon leaving the area.<ref name=\"LawrenceMay2003b\">{{cite book |vauthors=Lawrence J, May D |title=Infection control in the community |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKK2QI8AhTgC&pg=PA136 |year=2003 |publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences |isbn=978-0-443-06406-7 |page=136}}</ref>\n\n====Contact isolation====\n'''Contact isolation''' is used to prevent the spread of diseases that can be spread through contact with open wounds. Health care workers making contact with a patient on contact isolation are required to wear [[Medical gloves|gloves]], and in some cases, a [[Hospital gown|gown]].\n\n====Respiratory isolation====\n'''Respiratory isolation''' is used for diseases that are spread through particles that are [[exhalation|exhaled]].<ref name=\"Uys249\" /> Those having contact with or exposure to such a patient are required to wear a mask.\n\n====Reverse isolation====\n{{main|Reverse isolation}}\n[[File:Aeromedical Biological Containment System (ABCS).jpg|thumb|265px|The [[Aeromedical Biological Containment System]] (ABCS) is an air-transportable ''high isolation'' module for movement of highly contagious patients.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Matthew |name-list-format=vanc |title=The private jet NOBODY wants to fly on: Inside the air ambulance used to transport Ebola victims around America |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2796852/the-private-jet-wants-fly-inside-aircraft-used-transport-ebola-victims-america.html |access-date=26 October 2014 |work=Daily Mail (UK) |date=17 October 2014}}</ref>]]\n'''Reverse isolation''' is a way to prevent a patient in a compromised health situation from being contaminated by other people or objects. It often involves the use of laminar air flow and mechanical barriers (to avoid physical contact with others) to isolate the patient from any harmful pathogens present in the external environment.<ref name=\"titleChildren reared in a reverse isolation environment: effects on cognitive and emotional development\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Tamaroff MH, Nir Y, Straker N |year=1986 |title=Children reared in a reverse isolation environment: effects on cognitive and emotional development |url= |journal=J. Autism Dev. Disord. |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=415\u2013424 |doi=10.1007/bf01531708|pmid=3804957 }}</ref>\n\n====High isolation====\n'''High isolation''' is used to prevent the spread of unusually highly contagious, or high consequence, infectious diseases (e.g., smallpox, Ebola virus). It stipulates mandatory use of: (1) gloves (or double gloves if appropriate), (2) protective eyewear (goggles or face shield), (3) a waterproof gown (or total body Tyvek suit, if appropriate), and (4) a [[respirator]] (at least FFP2 or N95 NIOSH equivalent), ''not'' simply a surgical mask.<ref name=\"pmid18623980\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Puro V, Fusco FM, Lanini S, Nisii C, Ippolito G |title=Risk management of febrile respiratory illness in emergency departments |journal=The New Microbiologica |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=165\u201373 |date=April 2008 |pmid=18623980 |doi= |url=http://www.newmicrobiologica.org/PUB/allegati_pdf/2008/2/165.pdf}}</ref> Sometimes [[negative pressure room]]s or [[Respirator#Powered air-purifying respirators (PAPRs)|powered air-purifying respirators]] (PAPRs) are also used.\n\n====Self-isolation====\n{{main|Seclusion}}\n[[File:COVID-19 Warning Mount Pleasant South Carolina.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Traffic sign in [[South Carolina]] that encouraged people to 'stay home' during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Carolina|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].]]\n'''Self-isolation''' or '''home isolation'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-self-isolation-for-patients-undergoing-testing/advice-sheet-home-isolation|title=Advice for home isolation|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> is the act of voluntarily quarantining oneself to prevent infection of oneself or others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yalehealth.yale.edu/self-isolation-information|title=Self-Isolation Information {{!}} Yale Health|website=yalehealth.yale.edu|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/our-work/diseases-and-conditions/covid-19-novel-coronavirus/covid-19-novel-coronavirus-health-advice-general-public/covid-19-novel-coronavirus-self-isolation|title=COVID-19 (novel coronavirus) - Self-isolation|website=Ministry of Health NZ|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medical.mit.edu/faqs/faq-2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-n-cov-self-isolation-issues|title=FAQ: Self-isolation for the 2019 novel coronavirus (COVID-19) {{!}} MIT Medical|website=medical.mit.edu|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> \nThe practice became notable during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\nKey features are:\n\n:* staying at home\n:* separating oneself from other people\u2014for example, trying not to be in the same room as other people at the same time\n:* asking friends, family members or delivery services to carry out errands, such as getting groceries, medicines or other shopping\n:* asking delivery drivers to leave items outside for collection.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Editor|first=Sarah Boseley Health|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/27/coronavirus-what-is-self-isolation-quarantine|title=Coronavirus quarantine and self-isolation: your questions answered|date=2020-02-28|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-29|last2=Belam|first2=and Martin|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/self-isolation-advice/|title=Self-isolation advice|date=2020-02-28|website=nhs.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\nThe Irish [[Health Service Executive]] recommends regularly monitoring symptoms and not disposing of rubbish until the self-isolation ends,<ref name=HSE>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.hse.ie/conditions/coronavirus/self-isolation-and-limited-social-interaction.html|title=Restricted movements and self-isolation|website=www2.hse.ie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> warning also that \"self-isolation can be boring or frustrating. It may affect your mood and feelings. You may feel low, worried or have [[Sleeping problems|problems sleeping]]. You may find it helps to stay in touch with friends or relatives by phone or on [[social media]].\"<ref name=HSE />\n\nUK employers may provide [[Statutory sick pay|sick pay]] to support self-isolation. [[Citizens Advice]] says that people on [[Zero-hour contract|zero-hours contracts]] can also receive sick pay.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Joseph|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51506729|title=Should I self-isolate and how do I do it?|date=2020-03-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Isolation of health care workers ==\n[[File:WHO in PPE.jpg|thumb|265px|Isolation wards may need to be hastily improvised during epidemics such as in this image of [[WHO]] workers in [[Lagos, Nigeria]] managing Ebola patients in 2014.]]\n\nDisease isolation is relevant to the work and safety of health care workers. Health care workers may be regularly exposed to various types of illnesses and are at risk of getting sick. Disease spread can occur between a patient and a health care worker, even if the health care workers take all necessary precautions to minimize transmission, including proper hygiene and being up-to-date with vaccines. If a health care worker gets sick with a communicable disease, the possible spread may occur to other health care workers or susceptible patients within the health care facility. This can include patients with a weakened immune system and may be at risk for serious complications.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/infection-prevention/about/ipc/en/ |title=WHO {{!}} Infection prevention and control|website=WHO|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\nHealth care workers who become infected with certain contagious agents may not be permitted to work with patients for a period of time. The [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration|Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA)]] has implemented several standards and directives applicable to protecting health care workers from the spread of infectious agents. These include bloodborne pathogens, personal protective equipment, and respiratory protections. The CDC has also released resource for health care facilities to assist in assessing and reducing risk for occupational exposure to infectious diseases. The purpose of these standards and guidelines is to prevent the spread of disease to others in a health care facility.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.osha.gov/SLTC/healthcarefacilities/infectious_diseases.html |title=Safety and Health Topics {{!}} Healthcare - Infectious Diseases {{!}} Occupational Safety and Health Administration|website=www.osha.gov|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n== Consequences ==\nDisease isolation is rarely disputed for its importance in protecting others from disease. However, it is important to consider the consequences disease isolation may have on an individual. For instance, patients may not be able to receive visitors, and in turn, become [[Loneliness|lonely]]. Patients may experience depression, anxiety, and anger.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Furuno JP, Krein S, Lansing B, Mody L |title=Health care worker opinions on use of isolation precautions in long-term care facilities |journal=American Journal of Infection Control |volume=40 |issue=3 |pages=263\u20136 |date=April 2012 |pmid=21784557 |pmc=3526888 |doi=10.1016/j.ajic.2011.03.019}}</ref> Small children may feel their isolation is a punishment.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gostin LO |title=Law, ethics, and public health in the vaccination debates: politics of the measles outbreak |journal=JAMA |volume=313 |issue=11 |pages=1099\u2013100 |date=March 2015 |pmid=25675396 |doi=10.1001/jama.2015.1518}}</ref> Staff may need to spend more time with patients. Patients may not be able to receive certain types of care due to the risk that other patients may become contaminated. This includes forms of care that involve use of equipment common to all patients at the facility, or that involve transporting the patient to an area of the facility common to all patients. Given the impact of isolation on patients, social and emotional support may be needed.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gammon J, Hunt J |title=Source isolation and patient wellbeing in healthcare settings |journal=British Journal of Nursing |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=88\u201391 |date=January 2018 |pmid=29368561 |doi=10.12968/bjon.2018.27.2.88}}</ref>\n\nAlthough a majority of health care professionals advocate for disease isolation as an effective means of reducing disease transmission, some health care professionals are concerned with implementing such control protocols given the possible negative consequences on patients. Patients isolated with [[Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|Methicillin Resistant Staphylococcus Aureus]] (MRSA) can also be negatively impacted by having less documented care/bedside visits from attending and residents.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Masse V, Valiquette L, Boukhoudmi S, Bonenfant F, Talab Y, Carvalho JC, Alarie I, Carrier N, Farand P |title=Impact of methicillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus contact isolation units on medical care |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=e57057 |date=2013 |pmid=23451144 |pmc=3581535 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0057057 |bibcode=2013PLoSO...857057M}}</ref>\n\n== Ethics ==\n[[File:New isolation ward.jpg|thumb|The new Ebola isolation ward in Lagos, Nigeria provides more space and better treatment.]]\nDisease isolation serves as an important method to protect the general community from disease, especially in a hospital or community-wide outbreak. However, this intervention poses an ethical question on rights of the individual versus rights of the general community.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Aita |first=Mark |last2=Ragland |first2=Takeem |name-list-format=vanc |date=2015-01-01 |title=Ebola Scare and Measles Resurgence: Mandatory Isolation/quarantine and Vaccination |journal=Online Journal of Health Ethics |volume=11 |issue=2 |doi=10.18785/ojhe.1102.02 |issn=1551-4218}}</ref>\n\nInfectious diseases, including isolation precaution measures, are generally not considered a primary topic of importance in the field of bioethics in comparison to other topics such as [[euthanasia]], [[Assisted reproductive technology|assisted reproduction]], and [[Genetic engineering|genetics]]. Possible reasons as to why infectious diseases are not viewed as a primary topic in medical ethics include the following: bias for topics that are more high-tech, wealthy-world topics such as euthanasia and assisted reproduction, blinding optimism that infectious diseases are no longer a threat because of the success of antibiotics and vaccines, and the labeling of \"other\" among certain infectious diseases such as [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]], [[tuberculosis]], [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]], etc.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Selgelid MJ |title=Ethics and infectious disease |journal=Bioethics |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=272\u201389 |date=June 2005 |pmid=16167406 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-8519.2005.00441.x}}</ref>\n\nIn cases of disease outbreaks, isolation can be argued as an ethical and necessary precaution for protecting the community from further disease transmission. This can be seen during the 2014 Disneyland measles outbreak and 2014 Ebola outbreak. This can be justified using [[felicific calculus]] to predict the outcomes (consequences) of moral action between the individual rights versus the rights of the general public during disease isolation. This justifies that disease isolation is most likely to result in the greatest amount of positive outcomes for the largest number of people.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Aita MD, Mark C, Ragland MA, Takeem T |title=Ebola Scare and Measles Resurgence: Mandatory Isolation/quarantine and Vaccination. |journal=Online Journal of Health Ethics |date=2015 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=2 |doi=10.18785/ojhe.1102.02}}</ref>\n\nDisease isolation can also be justified as a morally legitimate ethical practice in public health based on the reciprocal relationship between the individual and the state. The individual is obligated to protect others by preventing further spread of disease, respect the instructions from public health authorities and sequester themselves in their homes and not attend public gatherings, and act as a first responder (if a healthcare professional) by providing services to protect and restore public health. The state, on the other hand, is obligated to provide support to individuals burdened as a result of restrictive measures (e.g. compensation for missed work, providing access to food and other necessities for those quarantined and isolated, assistance for first responders to balance personal/professional obligations), ensure several legal protections are in place for those subjected to restrictive measures and communicate all relevant information regarding the necessity of restriction.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Viens AM, Bensimon CM, Upshur RE |date=2009-06-01 |title=Your Liberty or Your Life: Reciprocity in the Use of Restrictive Measures in Contexts of Contagion |journal=Journal of Bioethical Inquiry |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=207\u2013217 |doi=10.1007/s11673-009-9149-2}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*{{annotated link|Seclusion}}\n*{{annotated link|Physical distancing}}\n*{{annotated link|Barrier nursing}}\n*{{annotated link|Body substance isolation}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=LILWN0VQuGQC&pg=RA1-PA250&lpg=RA1-PA249&dq=isolation+nursing&lr=&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html Chart showing recommendations for various forms of isolation]\n\n{{Health care}}\n\n[[Category:Infectious diseases]]\n[[Category:Prevention]]\n[[Category:Nursing]]\n[[Category:Medical hygiene]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Measure taken to prevent contagious diseases from being spread}}\n{{distinguish|biocontainment|quarantine}}\n{{other uses|Isolation (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:Tb ward.jpg|thumb|365px|This illustration of a TB ward from [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration|OSHA]] demonstrates several aspects of hospital [[infection control]] and '''isolation''': engineering controls (dedicated air ductwork), [[Personal protective equipment|PPE]] ([[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 respirators]]), warning signs and labels (controlled entry), dedicated disposal container, and enhanced housekeeping practices.]]\n\nIn [[health care facilities]], '''isolation''' represents one of several measures that can be taken to implement [[infection control]]: the prevention of [[contagious disease]]s from being spread from a [[patient]] to other patients, health care workers, and visitors, or from outsiders to a particular patient (reverse isolation). Various forms of isolation exist, in some of which contact procedures are modified, and others in which the patient is kept away from all others. In a system devised, and periodically revised, by the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC), various levels of patient isolation comprise application of one or more formally described \"precaution\".\n\nIsolation is most commonly used when a patient is known to have a contagious ([[Transmission (medicine)|transmissible]] from person-to-person) [[viral illness|viral]] or [[Bacteria|bacterial illness]].<ref name=\"LawrenceMay2003a\">{{cite book|author1=Lawrence J|author2=May D|title=Infection control in the community|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKK2QI8AhTgC&pg=PA136|year=2003|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-443-06406-7|page=136}}</ref> Special equipment is used in the management of patients in the various forms of isolation. These most commonly include items of [[personal protective equipment]] ([[cleanroom suit|gowns]], [[surgical mask|masks]], and [[medical glove|gloves]]) and engineering controls (positive pressure rooms, [[Negative room pressure|negative pressure rooms]], laminar air flow equipment, and various mechanical and structural barriers).<ref name=\"Uys249\">{{cite book|author=Uys LR|title=Fundamental nursing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LILWN0VQuGQC&pg=RA1-PA249|year=1999|publisher=Pearson South Africa|isbn=978-0-636-04208-7|page=249}}</ref> Dedicated [[isolation ward]]s may be pre-built into hospitals, or isolation units may be temporarily designated in facilities in the midst of an [[epidemic]] emergency.\n\n== Importance ==\n[[Infection|Contagious diseases]] can spread to others through various forms. Four types of infectious disease [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] can occur: (1) contact transmission, which can be through direct physical contact, indirect contact through fomites, or droplet contact in which airborne infections spread short distances, (2) vehicular transmission, which involves contaminated objects, (3) [[airborne transmission]], which involves spread of infectious particles through air, and (4) vector transmission, which is spread through insects or animals.<ref>{{cite book |vauthors=Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW, McCue JD |title=The Contagious Patient |date=1990 |url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK337/ |work=Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations |veditors=Walker HK, Dallas W, Willis J |edition=3rd |publisher=Butterworths |isbn=978-0-409-90077-4 |pmid=21250179}}</ref> Depending on the [[contagious disease]], transmission can occur within a person's home, school, worksite, health care facility, and other shared spaces within the community. Even if a person takes all necessary precautions to protect oneself from disease, such as being up-to-date with [[Vaccine|vaccines]] and practicing good [[hygiene]], he or she can still get sick. Some people may not be able to protect themselves from diseases and may develop serious complications if they contract the disease. Therefore, disease isolation is an important infection prevention and control practice used to protect others from disease.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Swanson J, Jeanes A |title=Infection control in the community: a pragmatic approach |journal=British Journal of Community Nursing |volume=16 |issue=6 |pages=282\u20138 |date=June 2011 |pmid=21642912 |doi=10.12968/bjcn.2011.16.6.282}}</ref> Disease isolation can prevent healthcare-acquired infections of [[Hospital-acquired infection|hospital-acquired infections]] (HCAIs), reduce threats of [[Antimicrobial resistance|antibiotic resistance infections]], and respond to new and emerging infectious disease threats globally.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gammon J, Hunt J |title=A review of isolation practices and procedures in healthcare settings |journal=British Journal of Nursing |volume=27 |issue=3 |pages=137\u2013140 |date=February 2018 |pmid=29412028 |doi=10.12968/bjon.2018.27.3.137}}</ref>\n\n== Types of precautions ==\nThe U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) created various levels of disease isolation (also described \"precaution\"). These precautions are also reviewed and revised by the CDC.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/infectioncontrol/basics/standard-precautions.html |title=Standard Precautions for All Patient Care {{!}} Basics {{!}} Infection Control {{!}} CDC|date=2019-03-25|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Universal/standard ===\n{{main|Universal precautions}}\n''Universal precautions''  refer to the practice, in [[medicine]], of avoiding contact with patients' bodily fluids, by means of the wearing of nonporous articles such as [[medical gloves]], [[goggles]], and [[face shield]]s. The practice was widely introduced in 1985\u201388.<ref name=\"pmid2836717\">{{cite journal |author=Centers for Disease Control (CDC) |title=Update: universal precautions for prevention of transmission of human immunodeficiency virus, hepatitis B virus, and other bloodborne pathogens in health-care settings |journal=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |volume=37 |issue=24 |pages=377\u201382, 387\u20138 |date=June 1988 |pmid=2836717 |doi= |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00000039.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid2997587\">{{cite journal |author=Centers for Disease Control (CDC) |title=Recommendations for preventing transmission of infection with human T-lymphotropic virus type III/lymphadenopathy-associated virus in the workplace |journal=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report |volume=34 |issue=45 |pages=681\u20136, 691\u20135 |date=November 1985 |pmid=2997587 |doi= |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00033093.htm}}</ref> In 1987, the practice of universal precautions was adjusted by a set of rules known as [[body substance isolation]]. In 1996, both practices were replaced by the latest approach known as standard precautions. Use of [[personal protective equipment]] is now recommended in all health settings.\n\n=== Transmission-based ===\n{{main|Transmission-based precautions}}\n\n''Transmission-based precautions'' are additional [[infection control]] precautions \u2013 over and above universal/standard precautions \u2013 and the latest routine infection prevention and control practices applied for patients who are known or suspected to be infected or colonized with infectious agents, including certain [[Epidemiology|epidemiologically]] important [[pathogen]]s. The latter require additional control measures to effectively prevent transmission.<ref name=\"autogenerated2007\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Siegel JD, Rhinehart E, Jackson M, Chiarello L |title=2007 Guideline for Isolation Precautions: Preventing Transmission of Infectious Agents in Health Care Settings |journal=American Journal of Infection Control |volume=35 |issue=10 Suppl 2 |pages=S65\u2013164 |date=December 2007 |pmid=18068815 |doi=10.1016/j.ajic.2007.10.007}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Infection prevention and control of epidemic- and pandemic-prone acute respiratory diseases in health care, WHO Interim Guidelines |date=2007 |page=53 ||</ref>There are three types of transmission-based precaution:\n*'''''Contact precautions''''' are intended to prevent transmission of infectious agents, including epidemiologically important [[microorganism]]s, which are spread by direct or indirect contact with the patient or the patient's environment.\n*'''''Droplet precautions''''' are intended to prevent transmission of pathogens spread through close respiratory or mucous membrane contact with respiratory secretions.\n*'''''Airborne precautions''''' prevent transmission of infectious agents that remain infectious over long distances when suspended in the air (e.g., rubeola virus [measles], varicella virus [chickenpox], M. tuberculosis, and possibly SARS-CoV).\n\n=== Isolation ===\nAccording to the CDC, isolation is used to protect the general public from possible exposure of a contagious disease. ''Isolation'' is the act of separating a sick individual with a contagious disease from healthy individuals without that contagious disease.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/index.html |title=Quarantine and Isolation {{!}} Quarantine {{!}} |date=2018-10-03| work = Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\nSpecial equipment is used in the management of patients in the various forms of isolation. These most commonly include items of [[personal protective equipment]] ([[Cleanroom suit|gowns]], [[Surgical mask|masks]], and [[Medical glove|gloves]]) and engineering controls (positive pressure rooms, negative pressure rooms, laminar air flow equipment, and various mechanical and structural barriers). Dedicated [[Isolation ward|isolation wards]] may be pre-built into hospitals, or isolation units may be temporarily designated in facilities in the midst of an epidemic emergency.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.loot.co.za/product/leana-uys-fundamental-nursing/mkkm-180-g460 |title=Fundamental Nursing - Textbook (Paperback) |publisher=Leana Uys |isbn=978-0-636-04208-7 |access-date=2019-05-01 |year=2003}}</ref>\n\nIsolation should not be mistaken as the same as [[quarantine]] or biocontainment. [[Quarantine]] is the compulsory separation and confinement, with restriction of movement, of healthy individuals or groups who have potentially been exposed to an agent to prevent further infections should infection occur. [[Biocontainment]] refers to laboratory biosafety in microbiology laboratories in which the physical containment (BSL-3, BSL-4) of highly pathogenic organisms is accomplished through built-in engineering controls.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/index.html |title=Quarantine and Isolation {{!}} Quarantine {{!}} | work = Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |date=2018-10-03 |access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\nMany forms of isolation exist.\n\n====Strict isolation====\n'''Strict isolation''' is used for diseases spread through the air and in some cases by contact.<ref name=\"Uys249\"/> Patients must be placed in isolation to prevent the spread of infectious diseases.<ref name=\"WHITE2004\">{{cite book |author=White L |title=Foundations of nursing |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xSFunA58p8gC&pg=PA757 |date=2004 |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-1-4018-2692-5 |page=757}}</ref> Those who are kept in strict isolation are often kept in a special room at the facility designed for that purpose. Such rooms are equipped with a special [[toilet|lavatory]] and caregiving equipment, and a sink and waste disposal are provided for workers upon leaving the area.<ref name=\"LawrenceMay2003b\">{{cite book |vauthors=Lawrence J, May D |title=Infection control in the community |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XKK2QI8AhTgC&pg=PA136 |year=2003 |publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences |isbn=978-0-443-06406-7 |page=136}}</ref>\n\n====Contact isolation====\n'''Contact isolation''' is used to prevent the spread of diseases that can be spread through contact with open wounds. Health care workers making contact with a patient on contact isolation are required to wear [[Medical gloves|gloves]], and in some cases, a [[Hospital gown|gown]].\n\n====Respiratory isolation====\n'''Respiratory isolation''' is used for diseases that are spread through particles that are [[exhalation|exhaled]].<ref name=\"Uys249\" /> Those having contact with or exposure to such a patient are required to wear a mask.\n\n====Reverse isolation====\n{{main|Reverse isolation}}\n[[File:Aeromedical Biological Containment System (ABCS).jpg|thumb|265px|The [[Aeromedical Biological Containment System]] (ABCS) is an air-transportable ''high isolation'' module for movement of highly contagious patients.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blake |first1=Matthew |name-list-format=vanc |title=The private jet NOBODY wants to fly on: Inside the air ambulance used to transport Ebola victims around America |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2796852/the-private-jet-wants-fly-inside-aircraft-used-transport-ebola-victims-america.html |access-date=26 October 2014 |work=Daily Mail (UK) |date=17 October 2014}}</ref>]]\n'''Reverse isolation''' is a way to prevent a patient in a compromised health situation from being contaminated by other people or objects. It often involves the use of laminar air flow and mechanical barriers (to avoid physical contact with others) to isolate the patient from any harmful pathogens present in the external environment.<ref name=\"titleChildren reared in a reverse isolation environment: effects on cognitive and emotional development\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Tamaroff MH, Nir Y, Straker N |year=1986 |title=Children reared in a reverse isolation environment: effects on cognitive and emotional development |url= |journal=J. Autism Dev. Disord. |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=415\u2013424 |doi=10.1007/bf01531708|pmid=3804957 }}</ref>\n\n====High isolation====\n'''High isolation''' is used to prevent the spread of unusually highly contagious, or high consequence, infectious diseases (e.g., smallpox, Ebola virus). It stipulates mandatory use of: (1) gloves (or double gloves if appropriate), (2) protective eyewear (goggles or face shield), (3) a waterproof gown (or total body Tyvek suit, if appropriate), and (4) a [[respirator]] (at least FFP2 or N95 NIOSH equivalent), ''not'' simply a surgical mask.<ref name=\"pmid18623980\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Puro V, Fusco FM, Lanini S, Nisii C, Ippolito G |title=Risk management of febrile respiratory illness in emergency departments |journal=The New Microbiologica |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=165\u201373 |date=April 2008 |pmid=18623980 |doi= |url=http://www.newmicrobiologica.org/PUB/allegati_pdf/2008/2/165.pdf}}</ref> Sometimes [[negative pressure room]]s or [[Respirator#Powered air-purifying respirators (PAPRs)|powered air-purifying respirators]] (PAPRs) are also used.\n\n====Self-isolation====\n{{main|Seclusion}}\n[[File:COVID-19 Warning Mount Pleasant South Carolina.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Traffic sign in [[South Carolina]] that encouraged people to 'stay home' during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Carolina|2020 coronavirus pandemic]].]]\n'''Self-isolation''' or '''home isolation'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/wuhan-novel-coronavirus-self-isolation-for-patients-undergoing-testing/advice-sheet-home-isolation|title=Advice for home isolation|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> is the act of voluntarily quarantining oneself to prevent infection of oneself or others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yalehealth.yale.edu/self-isolation-information|title=Self-Isolation Information {{!}} Yale Health|website=yalehealth.yale.edu|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/our-work/diseases-and-conditions/covid-19-novel-coronavirus/covid-19-novel-coronavirus-health-advice-general-public/covid-19-novel-coronavirus-self-isolation|title=COVID-19 (novel coronavirus) - Self-isolation|website=Ministry of Health NZ|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medical.mit.edu/faqs/faq-2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-n-cov-self-isolation-issues|title=FAQ: Self-isolation for the 2019 novel coronavirus (COVID-19) {{!}} MIT Medical|website=medical.mit.edu|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> \nThe practice became notable during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\nKey features are:\n\n:* staying at home\n:* separating oneself from other people\u2014for example, trying not to be in the same room as other people at the same time\n:* asking friends, family members or delivery services to carry out errands, such as getting groceries, medicines or other shopping\n:* asking delivery drivers to leave items outside for collection.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Editor|first=Sarah Boseley Health|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/27/coronavirus-what-is-self-isolation-quarantine|title=Coronavirus quarantine and self-isolation: your questions answered|date=2020-02-28|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-29|last2=Belam|first2=and Martin|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/self-isolation-advice/|title=Self-isolation advice|date=2020-02-28|website=nhs.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\nThe Irish [[Health Service Executive]] recommends regularly monitoring symptoms and not disposing of rubbish until the self-isolation ends,<ref name=HSE>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.hse.ie/conditions/coronavirus/self-isolation-and-limited-social-interaction.html|title=Restricted movements and self-isolation|website=www2.hse.ie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> warning also that \"self-isolation can be boring or frustrating. It may affect your mood and feelings. You may feel low, worried or have [[Sleeping problems|problems sleeping]]. You may find it helps to stay in touch with friends or relatives by phone or on [[social media]].\"<ref name=HSE />\n\nUK employers may provide [[Statutory sick pay|sick pay]] to support self-isolation. [[Citizens Advice]] says that people on [[Zero-hour contract|zero-hours contracts]] can also receive sick pay.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lee|first=Joseph|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51506729|title=Should I self-isolate and how do I do it?|date=2020-03-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n'''Bold text'''== Isolation of health care workers ==\n[[File:WHO in PPE.jpg|thumb|265px|Isolation wards may need to be hastily improvised during epidemics such as in this image of [[WHO]] workers in [[Lagos, Nigeria]] managing Ebola patients in 2014.]]\n\nDisease isolation is relevant to the work and safety of health care workers. Health care workers may be regularly exposed to various types of illnesses and are at risk of getting sick. Disease spread can occur between a patient and a health care worker, even if the health care workers take all necessary precautions to minimize transmission, including proper hygiene and being up-to-date with vaccines. If a health care worker gets sick with a communicable disease, the possible spread may occur to other health care workers or susceptible patients within the health care facility. This can include patients with a weakened immune system and may be at risk for serious complications.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.who.int/infection-prevention/about/ipc/en/ |title=WHO {{!}} Infection prevention and control|website=WHO|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\nHealth care workers who become infected with certain contagious agents may not be permitted to work with patients for a period of time. The [[Occupational Safety and Health Administration|Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA)]] has implemented several standards and directives applicable to protecting health care workers from the spread of infectious agents. These include bloodborne pathogens, personal protective equipment, and respiratory protections. The CDC has also released resource for health care facilities to assist in assessing and reducing risk for occupational exposure to infectious diseases. The purpose of these standards and guidelines is to prevent the spread of disease to others in a health care facility.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.osha.gov/SLTC/healthcarefacilities/infectious_diseases.html |title=Safety and Health Topics {{!}} Healthcare - Infectious Diseases {{!}} Occupational Safety and Health Administration|website=www.osha.gov|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n== Consequences ==\nDisease isolation is rarely disputed for its importance in protecting others from disease. However, it is important to consider the consequences disease isolation may have on an individual. For instance, patients may not be able to receive visitors, and in turn, become [[Loneliness|lonely]]. Patients may experience depression, anxiety, and anger.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Furuno JP, Krein S, Lansing B, Mody L |title=Health care worker opinions on use of isolation precautions in long-term care facilities |journal=American Journal of Infection Control |volume=40 |issue=3 |pages=263\u20136 |date=April 2012 |pmid=21784557 |pmc=3526888 |doi=10.1016/j.ajic.2011.03.019}}</ref> Small children may feel their isolation is a punishment.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gostin LO |title=Law, ethics, and public health in the vaccination debates: politics of the measles outbreak |journal=JAMA |volume=313 |issue=11 |pages=1099\u2013100 |date=March 2015 |pmid=25675396 |doi=10.1001/jama.2015.1518}}</ref> Staff may need to spend more time with patients. Patients may not be able to receive certain types of care due to the risk that other patients may become contaminated. This includes forms of care that involve use of equipment common to all patients at the facility, or that involve transporting the patient to an area of the facility common to all patients. Given the impact of isolation on patients, social and emotional support may be needed.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gammon J, Hunt J |title=Source isolation and patient wellbeing in healthcare settings |journal=British Journal of Nursing |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=88\u201391 |date=January 2018 |pmid=29368561 |doi=10.12968/bjon.2018.27.2.88}}</ref>\n\nAlthough a majority of health care professionals advocate for disease isolation as an effective means of reducing disease transmission, some health care professionals are concerned with implementing such control protocols given the possible negative consequences on patients. Patients isolated with [[Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|Methicillin Resistant Staphylococcus Aureus]] (MRSA) can also be negatively impacted by having less documented care/bedside visits from attending and residents.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Masse V, Valiquette L, Boukhoudmi S, Bonenfant F, Talab Y, Carvalho JC, Alarie I, Carrier N, Farand P |title=Impact of methicillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus contact isolation units on medical care |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=e57057 |date=2013 |pmid=23451144 |pmc=3581535 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0057057 |bibcode=2013PLoSO...857057M}}</ref>\n\n== Ethics ==\n[[File:New isolation ward.jpg|thumb|The new Ebola isolation ward in Lagos, Nigeria provides more space and better treatment.]]\nDisease isolation serves as an important method to protect the general community from disease, especially in a hospital or community-wide outbreak. However, this intervention poses an ethical question on rights of the individual versus rights of the general community.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Aita |first=Mark |last2=Ragland |first2=Takeem |name-list-format=vanc |date=2015-01-01 |title=Ebola Scare and Measles Resurgence: Mandatory Isolation/quarantine and Vaccination |journal=Online Journal of Health Ethics |volume=11 |issue=2 |doi=10.18785/ojhe.1102.02 |issn=1551-4218}}</ref>\n\nInfectious diseases, including isolation precaution measures, are generally not considered a primary topic of importance in the field of bioethics in comparison to other topics such as [[euthanasia]], [[Assisted reproductive technology|assisted reproduction]], and [[Genetic engineering|genetics]]. Possible reasons as to why infectious diseases are not viewed as a primary topic in medical ethics include the following: bias for topics that are more high-tech, wealthy-world topics such as euthanasia and assisted reproduction, blinding optimism that infectious diseases are no longer a threat because of the success of antibiotics and vaccines, and the labeling of \"other\" among certain infectious diseases such as [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]], [[tuberculosis]], [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]], etc.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Selgelid MJ |title=Ethics and infectious disease |journal=Bioethics |volume=19 |issue=3 |pages=272\u201389 |date=June 2005 |pmid=16167406 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-8519.2005.00441.x}}</ref>\n\nIn cases of disease outbreaks, isolation can be argued as an ethical and necessary precaution for protecting the community from further disease transmission. This can be seen during the 2014 Disneyland measles outbreak and 2014 Ebola outbreak. This can be justified using [[felicific calculus]] to predict the outcomes (consequences) of moral action between the individual rights versus the rights of the general public during disease isolation. This justifies that disease isolation is most likely to result in the greatest amount of positive outcomes for the largest number of people.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Aita MD, Mark C, Ragland MA, Takeem T |title=Ebola Scare and Measles Resurgence: Mandatory Isolation/quarantine and Vaccination. |journal=Online Journal of Health Ethics |date=2015 |volume=11 |issue=2 |pages=2 |doi=10.18785/ojhe.1102.02}}</ref>\n\nDisease isolation can also be justified as a morally legitimate ethical practice in public health based on the reciprocal relationship between the individual and the state. The individual is obligated to protect others by preventing further spread of disease, respect the instructions from public health authorities and sequester themselves in their homes and not attend public gatherings, and act as a first responder (if a healthcare professional) by providing services to protect and restore public health. The state, on the other hand, is obligated to provide support to individuals burdened as a result of restrictive measures (e.g. compensation for missed work, providing access to food and other necessities for those quarantined and isolated, assistance for first responders to balance personal/professional obligations), ensure several legal protections are in place for those subjected to restrictive measures and communicate all relevant information regarding the necessity of restriction.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Viens AM, Bensimon CM, Upshur RE |date=2009-06-01 |title=Your Liberty or Your Life: Reciprocity in the Use of Restrictive Measures in Contexts of Contagion |journal=Journal of Bioethical Inquiry |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=207\u2013217 |doi=10.1007/s11673-009-9149-2}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*{{annotated link|Seclusion}}\n*{{annotated link|Physical distancing}}\n*{{annotated link|Barrier nursing}}\n*{{annotated link|Body substance isolation}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=LILWN0VQuGQC&pg=RA1-PA250&lpg=RA1-PA249&dq=isolation+nursing&lr=&ie=ISO-8859-1&output=html Chart showing recommendations for various forms of isolation]\n\n{{Health care}}\n\n[[Category:Infectious diseases]]\n[[Category:Prevention]]\n[[Category:Nursing]]\n[[Category:Medical hygiene]]\n", "name_user": "Catlemur", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isolation_(health_care)"}
